<TITLE> Malaysia's Mahathir recovering after surgery </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUALA LUMPUR, Oct 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Former Malaysian prime minister Mahathir Mohamad was moved out of an intensive care unit on Monday following surgery for a chest infection caused by a heart bypass, the hospital treating him said. Mahathir, the country's longest-serving premier, remains an influential political figure even though he has fallen out with his successor, Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, over policy changes made since his retirement. The 82-year-old leader had quadruple bypass surgery on Sept 4, but needed a second operation on Sept 22 to counter the infection, and had been in intensive care since, though recovering steadily. "Things are looking up," Mahathir's eldest daughter Marina said on her Internet blog, which carried two pictures of herself and her mother with Mahathir in hospital, looking pale and tired, but cheerful, just before the transfer around noon on Monday. "Doesn't he look good?" Marina added. "Had lunch of spaghetti marinara, salad, fruit and pudding after that." The Sept 4 operation was Mahathir's second such surgery since 1989 and followed two heart attacks over the past 10 months. "Doctors are happy with his progress," the hospital said in a statement, adding that the former premier would continue with chest and muscle-strengthening exercises. "Dr Mahathir has also been able to walk unaided since yesterday." The outspoken Mahathir, who stepped down in 2003 after 22 years in office, had accused Western financiers led by George Soros of having bet against Asian currencies and contributed to the subsequent 1997-98 economic meltdo
